\subsection*{Key Features}

Nemotron-Content-Safety-Reasoning-4B has several notable technical characteristics relevant to its deployment as a content safety classifier.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Dual-mode operation}: The model supports two operating modes. In \textit{Reasoning Off} mode (\texttt{/no\_think}), it performs low-latency classification without producing an explicit reasoning trace, making it more suitable for high-throughput deployment contexts. In \textit{Reasoning On} mode (\texttt{/think}), the model generates a reasoning trace enclosed within \texttt{<think>...</think>} tags before producing a final safety judgement. This mode may improve performance on ambiguous or novel policy scenarios, but it also introduces greater computational cost and latency.

    \item \textbf{Sub-symbolic architecture}: The model is built on \textbf{Google Gemma-3-4B-it}, a 4-billion-parameter decoder-only Transformer. Its operation is therefore fundamentally \textit{sub-symbolic}, in the sense that it derives safety-relevant representations from training data through statistical learning rather than from explicitly hand-coded rules. However, the model is prompted to reason within a structured 22-category harm taxonomy (S1--S22), meaning that a symbolic policy structure is imposed at the prompt level on top of a sub-symbolic model core.

    \item \textbf{Training data -- Aegis AI Content Safety Dataset 2.0}: The model is fine-tuned on the Aegis AI Content Safety Dataset 2.0 \cite{ghosh2024aegis2}, a curated dataset containing 33,416 annotated prompt-response pairs (30,007 training, 1,445 validation, and 1,964 test examples), licensed under CC-BY-4.0. According to the dataset documentation, annotations were produced by 12 US-based crowdworkers, while prompts were drawn from sources including the Anthropic HH-RLHF dataset, DAN jailbreak prompts, and red-teaming outputs. The limited demographic diversity of annotators is an important ethical issue and is examined further in Chapter 2.

    \item \textbf{Custom policy adaptation}: Unlike fixed-rule content filters, the model can be adapted to alternative or extended safety definitions by modifying the policy text provided in the prompt. In principle, this allows operators to redefine what counts as harmful content for different application settings. This flexibility increases practical usefulness, but it also raises concerns about inconsistent policy enforcement and operator-dependent norm setting.

    \item \textbf{Computational efficiency}: With 4 billion parameters and a context window of up to 128K tokens, the model is designed to operate with a comparatively modest hardware footprint. NVIDIA indicates that deployment is feasible on GPUs with at least 16~GB VRAM, making the model more accessible than substantially larger safety classifiers.

    \item \textbf{Integration with NeMo Guardrails}: The model is designed for direct integration with the NVIDIA NeMo Guardrails framework, which provides a configurable deployment pipeline through files such as \texttt{config.yml} and \texttt{prompts.yml}. This enables the classifier to function as an input and output moderation layer for a wide range of LLM-based applications.
\end{itemize}

\section{Functional Goals of the System}

According to NVIDIA's documentation, the functional goals of Nemotron-Content-Safety-Reasoning-4B can be summarised as follows:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Input harm detection}: Classify each incoming user message against the 22-category harm taxonomy in order to determine whether the prompt is harmful before it is passed to the primary LLM.

    \item \textbf{Output harm detection}: Classify each LLM-generated response against the same taxonomy before it is returned to the user.

    \item \textbf{Refusal triggering}: Suppress the primary LLM's response and substitute a safe fallback message (for example, ``I'm sorry, I can't respond to that.'') when harmful content is detected.

    \item \textbf{Transparent reasoning (optional)}: When reasoning mode is enabled, provide an explicit reasoning trace alongside the safety judgement. This is intended to improve auditability in ambiguous or high-stakes cases, although it may introduce additional latency and interpretability concerns of its own.

    \item \textbf{Custom policy enforcement}: Allow operators to adapt the default safety policy by defining domain-specific harm categories or replacing the default taxonomy entirely.

    \item \textbf{Low-latency real-time classification}: Support inference speeds suitable for deployment as an inline safety filter in real-time conversational AI systems.

    \item \textbf{Empirically evaluated classification}: Demonstrate measurable precision, recall, and F1 performance on the held-out Aegis 2.0 test split (1,964 samples), thereby providing a benchmarked performance baseline for downstream deployment and evaluation \cite{ghosh2024aegis2}.
\end{enumerate}

