\chapter{Stakeholder Identification}

We identify the following primary and secondary stakeholders of the Nemotron-Content-Safety-Reasoning-4B system, organised by the STEEPLE framework:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Social:} End users of LLM-powered applications (e.g., chatbot users, students, patients seeking health information); vulnerable populations (minors, individuals experiencing mental health crises); journalists and researchers who may trigger false positives when investigating harmful topics; and marginalised communities whose dialects or cultural expressions may be systematically misclassified.

    \item \textbf{Technical:} NVIDIA (model developer and maintainer); application developers integrating NeMo Guardrails; operators of LLM platforms (e.g., healthcare providers, education platforms, enterprise chatbot vendors); and the primary LLMs (e.g., GPT-4o) whose outputs are filtered.

    \item \textbf{Economic:} Commercial operators who use the guardrail to reduce legal and reputational liability; NVIDIA, whose commercial interest is served by adoption of its open-source guardrail ecosystem; competing content moderation vendors (e.g., Perspective API by Google); and open-source community contributors who extend the model.

    \item \textbf{Ecological/Environmental:} Data centres running GPU inference on the 4B-parameter classifier consume energy on every single message; communities and ecosystems affected by the carbon footprint of large-scale AI inference infrastructure.

    \item \textbf{Political:} Governments and regulatory bodies establishing AI safety and content moderation standards (e.g., the EU AI Act); civil liberties organisations concerned with AI-driven censorship and freedom of expression; and state actors who may pressure operators to configure safety policies that suppress political speech under category S18 (Political Misinformation/Conspiracy).

    \item \textbf{Legal:} Legal teams of platform operators managing liability for harmful AI outputs; regulators enforcing compliance with GDPR (S9: PII/Privacy), child protection legislation (S7), and platform liability frameworks such as the EU Digital Services Act; and NVIDIA itself, operating under the NVIDIA Open Model Licence.

    \item \textbf{Invisible Stakeholders -- Aegis 2.0 Annotators:} The 12 US-based crowdworkers who annotated the Aegis 2.0 training data \cite{ghosh2024aegis2} are an invisible but foundational stakeholder group. Their demographic concentration determines whose intuitions about harm are encoded at the model's core. They are not named, their compensation is undisclosed, and their individual label decisions have been averaged away -- yet their judgements govern every classification the system makes.
\end{itemize}

Each stakeholder category carries distinct ethical principles applicable from multiple schools of thought. Social stakeholders invoke \textit{human dignity} and \textit{non-maleficence} (from deontological and virtue ethics). Technical and Economic stakeholders invoke \textit{beneficence}, \textit{accuracy}, and \textit{fairness}. Political and Legal stakeholders invoke \textit{justice}, \textit{autonomy}, and \textit{accountability} -- central concerns in both contractarian and relational ethics traditions.

Typically, the primary actors (end users and platform operators) maintain a minimum functional-to-ethical goals ratio of approximately $5:1$: the system exists primarily to moderate content at scale, and the ethical goals -- though more difficult to implement -- do not overshadow its functional purpose.

\section{Ethical Goals of the System}

NVIDIA's model card and NeMo Guardrails documentation suggest several implicit ethical goals for Nemotron-Content-Safety-Reasoning-4B:

\begin{itemize}
    \item to reduce the generation and propagation of harmful content across 22 predefined harm categories;
    \item to provide some degree of transparency regarding model limitations, including the risks of false positives and false negatives, through public documentation;
    \item to support customisation, allowing operators to adapt safety policy to particular deployment settings and community standards; and
    \item to make the model publicly available under the NVIDIA Open Model Licence, thereby enabling external scrutiny and downstream responsible use.
\end{itemize}

At the same time, NVIDIA does \textbf{not} publicly articulate explicit commitments to fairness across demographic groups, to mitigating the environmental impact of inference, or to providing mechanisms through which users can appeal or contest a safety classification. These omissions represent significant ethical gaps and form a central focus of this report.

\section{Ethical Considerations}

This report evaluates the system through three ethical frameworks: \textbf{Kantian deontology}, \textbf{utilitarianism}, and \textbf{Value-Sensitive Design (VSD)}.

\subsection*{School 1: Kantian Deontology}

Kantian ethics holds that actions should be governed by universal moral duties and that persons must always be treated as ends in themselves rather than merely as means. In this framework, the moral acceptability of a safety system depends not only on its outcomes, but also on whether it respects the rational agency of those subject to it.

\textbf{Case A -- False positive suppression.} If the classifier incorrectly flags a legitimate query, such as a medical request about overdose thresholds for clinical purposes or a research query concerning extremist rhetoric for counter-radicalisation work, the user may be blocked without adequate contextual consideration. From a Kantian perspective, a system that suppresses all discussion of sensitive topics irrespective of context risks failing the test of universalisation, because such a rule could not reasonably be willed as a general norm for rational discourse. It also risks treating the user merely as a potential source of harm to be managed, rather than as an agent capable of justified and legitimate inquiry.

\textit{Recommendation:} A more ethically defensible design would incorporate contextual signals into classification decisions. For example, a soft context-flag mechanism could allow users to declare relevant professional roles (e.g., \texttt{role: medical}), which would then be passed to the classifier as additional contextual information. This would not eliminate the risk of misuse, but it would better respect legitimate context-dependent inquiry.

\textbf{Case B -- Transparency of refusal.} At present, the system may return only a generic refusal message such as ``I'm sorry, I can't respond to that.'' From a Kantian standpoint, this is ethically problematic because decisions that constrain users' access to information should, where possible, be accompanied by some form of justification. An opaque refusal risks treating the user as an object of behavioural control rather than as a rational person entitled to an explanation.

\textit{Recommendation:} Refusal messages should indicate at least the relevant harm category, for example, ``This message has been flagged under category S3: Criminal Planning.'' Full internal reasoning traces need not be shown in production, but some meaningful explanation should be provided.

\subsection*{School 2: Utilitarianism}

Utilitarianism evaluates actions according to their consequences and seeks to maximise overall welfare across all affected parties. Applied to content moderation, this requires balancing the harms of false positives against the harms of false negatives, while taking into account both severity and scale.

\textbf{Case C -- Threshold calibration and false negatives.} A lenient threshold may reduce unnecessary blocking for benign users, but it may also permit genuinely harmful outputs, such as self-harm instructions, to reach vulnerable individuals. Conversely, a strict threshold may reduce harmful outputs while also suppressing legitimate requests. A utilitarian approach therefore requires threshold calibration that minimises total expected harm across both error types, with greater weight given to categories where false negatives are especially dangerous.

\textit{Recommendation:} Thresholds should be calibrated on a per-category basis. Categories such as S6 (Suicide and Self-Harm), S7 (Child Sexual Abuse Material), and S16 (Malware) warrant stricter settings, whereas lower-severity categories such as S12 (Profanity) and S13 (Needs Caution) may justify more permissive thresholds.

\textbf{Case D -- Dual-mode latency trade-off.} Reasoning mode (\texttt{/think}) may improve classification quality in ambiguous cases, but it also increases computational cost and latency. From a utilitarian perspective, the benefits of greater accuracy must be weighed against the costs imposed on all users and against the additional resource consumption of more expensive inference.

\textit{Recommendation:} For high-volume real-time deployments, \texttt{/no\_think} should be the default operational mode, while \texttt{/think} is better reserved for asynchronous audit, escalation, or review of edge cases.

\subsection*{School 3: Value-Sensitive Design (VSD)}

Value-Sensitive Design (VSD) argues that human values should be explicitly identified and incorporated into technical systems through conceptual, empirical, and technical investigation \cite{friedman1996value}. This is particularly relevant for content safety systems, since such systems embed normative judgments about acceptable speech, risk, and harm.

\textbf{Case E -- Misclassification affecting marginalised communities.} Nemotron-Content-Safety-Reasoning-4B is fine-tuned on Aegis 2.0, which was annotated by 12 US-based crowdworkers. This limited annotator base may over-represent dominant cultural and linguistic norms. As a result, forms of expression associated with African American Vernacular English (AAVE), LGBTQ+ communities, or politically coded speech may face disproportionate risk of being classified as S8 (Hate/Identity Hate) or S22 (Immoral/Unethical Content) \cite{ghosh2024aegis2}. Such a pattern would impose disproportionate burdens on already marginalised groups and would conflict with VSD's commitment to fairness and freedom from bias.

\textit{Recommendation:} Identity-related content that triggers sensitive categories should not always be automatically blocked. In higher-risk cases, routing such outputs to human review would be more defensible than immediate suppression. In addition, NVIDIA should publish subgroup-specific false positive and false negative analyses where feasible.

\textbf{Case F -- Operator accountability for custom policies.} VSD also highlights the importance of accountability. Because the system allows operators to redefine what counts as harmful, significant normative power is transferred from NVIDIA to downstream deployers. In principle, this flexibility could be used not only for legitimate contextual adaptation, but also for suppressing political speech, restricting criticism, or filtering competitor references. Without disclosure, users may not know whose policy is being enforced or how to challenge it.

\textit{Recommendation:} Refusal messages should identify that moderation has occurred under an operator-defined policy, for example: ``This response has been filtered according to [Operator Name]'s content policy.'' This would not solve all accountability problems, but it would improve transparency and make responsibility more visible.

\section{Values}

The system brings several stakeholder groups into tension, each with partially overlapping and partially conflicting values:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{End users (social):} value \textit{autonomy}, \textit{dignity}, and \textit{transparency}. Users have an interest in accessing information, in not being treated as presumptively dangerous, and in receiving understandable explanations for moderation decisions.

    \item \textbf{NVIDIA (technical/economic):} values \textit{adoption}, \textit{reputation}, and \textit{safety}. These goals may align with broad utilitarian aims, but they can also conflict with stronger forms of transparency if opacity better protects the product or reduces liability.

    \item \textbf{Application operators (technical/economic/legal):} value \textit{compliance}, \textit{risk mitigation}, and \textit{customisability}. These aims may conflict with user autonomy where operators adopt overly restrictive or poorly disclosed policies.

    \item \textbf{Regulators (political/legal):} value \textit{accountability}, \textit{proportionality}, and \textit{non-discrimination}. These values often support VSD-oriented concerns, but may constrain operator flexibility and increase compliance burdens.

    \item \textbf{Marginalised communities (social):} value \textit{freedom from bias}, \textit{equal treatment}, and \textit{voice}. These interests merit particular attention because such groups are more likely to bear the burden of systematic misclassification while having less power to contest automated decisions.
\end{itemize}

The most important ethical tension lies between the values of end users and marginalised communities, on the one hand, and those of operators and platform providers, on the other. In this report, user autonomy and freedom from bias are treated as especially important because content safety classifiers exercise substantial control over access to information, and the costs of misclassification are often borne most heavily by those with the least procedural power.

