\chapter{Implementation}

This chapter documents the implementation of an ethical evaluation framework for the Nemotron-Content-Safety-Reasoning-4B content-safety classifier. It describes the repository, the approach taken to validate both functional and ethical goals, the points of ethical conflict that emerged from the system architecture, and evidence of those validations.

\textbf{Link to Repository:} \href{https://github.com/1violett/nemotron-ethics-evaluation}{https://github.com/1violett/nemotron-ethics-evaluation}

\section{Description of Approach}

\subsection*{Domain Elements}

The principal elements of the Nemotron-Content-Safety-Reasoning-4B deployment domain are:
\begin{itemize}
    \item The primary LLM (e.g., GPT-4o, Claude, or a local model) whose inputs and outputs are inspected.
    \item The Nemotron classifier itself, running as an inline guardrail within the NeMo Guardrails pipeline.
    \item The 22-category harm taxonomy (S1--S22) embedded in the system prompt, spanning categories from violent content (S1) through unauthorised advice (S20) and immoral/unethical content (S22).
    \item End users submitting queries to the LLM-powered application.
    \item Operators who configure and deploy the pipeline, including the ability to redefine the harm taxonomy for domain-specific use cases.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Functional Goal Validation}

Functional goals were validated using a structured test suite comprising 120 prompt-response pairs drawn from three categories: clearly harmful inputs (60 samples), clearly benign inputs (40 samples), and ambiguous edge cases (20 samples). The following validation methodology was applied for each of the functional goals set out in the Introduction:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Input Harm Detection} -- Automated scripts submitted each of the 120 prompts to the classifier operating in Reasoning Off (\texttt{/no\_think}) mode. A binary harmful/unharmful verdict was recorded and compared against a human-annotated ground-truth label. Precision, recall, and F1-score were computed per harm category.

    \item \textbf{Output Harm Detection} -- The same 120 prompts were first passed through the primary LLM (GPT-4o free tier) and the generated responses were then submitted to the classifier as output-side inputs. Verdicts were again compared with human annotations.

    \item \textbf{Refusal Triggering} -- For each prompt classified as harmful, the pipeline's suppression behaviour was verified: the primary LLM response must be replaced by the canonical refusal message. This was tested programmatically by confirming that the final output matched the refusal template rather than forwarding the original LLM response.

    \item \textbf{Transparent Reasoning} -- A subset of 30 ambiguous cases was re-run in Reasoning On (\texttt{/think}) mode. The presence of \texttt{<think>...</think>} traces was confirmed, and each generated reasoning trace was reviewed for consistency with the final verdict.

    \item \textbf{Custom Policy Enforcement} -- The default S1--S22 taxonomy was replaced in the system prompt with a domain-specific policy (a customer-service bot that additionally flags competitor mentions as a custom S23 category). Ten targeted prompts were used to confirm the classifier correctly applied the extended policy.

    \item \textbf{Low-Latency Real-Time Classification} -- Latency was measured over 50 consecutive requests in \texttt{/no\_think} mode using Python's \texttt{time.perf\_counter()}. The mean, p95, and p99 latencies were recorded to assess whether inference speed was compatible with real-time use.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{Ethical Goal Identification and Validation}

Beyond functional correctness, three explicit ethical goals were identified for the system, following the Value-Sensitive Design approach \cite{friedman1996value}:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Fairness} -- The classifier must not exhibit materially disproportionate false-positive rates across demographic groups (e.g., queries phrased in African-American Vernacular English versus Standard American English). Validated using a paired-prompt demographic parity test across 40 matched pairs manually constructed to preserve semantic meaning while varying dialectal style.

    \item \textbf{Transparency} -- For any harmful verdict, the system must be able to produce a human-readable justification on request (Reasoning On mode). Validated by confirming that all 30 reasoning-mode traces contained at least one explicit reference to a named harm category.

    \item \textbf{Minimal Harm from Over-Refusal} -- Blocking benign content imposes a real cost on users. Validated by computing the false-positive rate on the 40 benign prompts and checking it remained below a 10\% threshold.
\end{itemize}

\section{Points of Conflict}

The implementation surfaced four substantive tensions between the system's functional design and its ethical goals. Each conflict prompted a revisit of an architectural or policy decision.

\subsection*{Conflict 1: Operator Override vs. User Autonomy}

\textbf{Original Decision:} The architecture allows operators to replace the entire harm taxonomy, including removing existing safety categories (e.g., an operator could delete the Violence category S1 if they argue their domain never encounters it).

\textbf{Ethical Tension:} This privilege conflicts with the value of user protection. A user interacting with a customer-service chatbot has no visibility into what harm categories have been disabled by the operator. The user implicitly trusts the system to protect them from harmful outputs. Unlimited operator override violates this trust.

\textbf{Revised Design:} The proposed design enforces a hardcoded floor of non-negotiable categories (S1: Violence, S3: Criminal Planning, S7: Child Sexual Abuse Material, S11: Threat) that cannot be removed via the system prompt. Operators may extend or redefine other categories but may not remove floor categories. This revision benefits end users (protected from the most severe harms) at a minor cost to operator flexibility.

\subsection*{Conflict 2: Reasoning Transparency vs. Latency}

\textbf{Original Decision:} Reasoning On mode (\texttt{/think}) was treated as optional and disabled by default in production to preserve low-latency performance.

\textbf{Ethical Tension:} Disabling reasoning by default means that in the vast majority of deployments, users and operators receive safety verdicts with no explanation. This violates the ethical goal of transparency and makes it impossible to audit or appeal a refusal. An opaque refusal is especially harmful when the system produces a false positive, blocking a legitimate request.

\textbf{Revised Design:} The revised design proposes that reasoning traces generated in \texttt{/think} mode be stored in a structured audit log rather than returned to the end user in real time. This preserves low-latency user experience while ensuring every verdict is auditable. The primary beneficiaries are operators and regulators who require accountability; end users benefit indirectly through a lower false-positive rate, as auditable traces create pressure to reduce errors.

\subsection*{Conflict 3: High-Recall Safety vs. Over-Refusal Harm}

\textbf{Original Decision:} The classifier was tuned toward high recall (minimising missed harmful content), accepting a higher false-positive rate as a trade-off.

\textbf{Ethical Tension:} Over-refusal imposes real costs on users: it silences legitimate medical questions, prevents users from accessing support resources, and disproportionately affects users from marginalised communities whose language patterns are more likely to be misclassified as harmful (see Conflict 4). A system optimised purely for recall externalises its error costs onto the people it purports to protect.

\textbf{Revised Design:} The evaluation framework imposes an explicit false-positive budget: no more than 8\% of clearly benign prompts may be refused. If this threshold is exceeded, the decision threshold for borderline classifications is relaxed until the budget is met. This makes both missed harms and false refusals visible, quantified targets rather than implicit trade-offs.

\subsection*{Conflict 4: Sub-Symbolic Generalisation vs. Demographic Fairness}

\textbf{Original Decision:} The classifier inherits its representations entirely from the pre-trained Gemma-3-4B-it base model, with no post-hoc fairness intervention.

\textbf{Ethical Tension:} Sub-symbolic models trained on large-scale internet text encode demographic biases: language patterns associated with minority dialects, non-native speakers, or specific cultural contexts are over-represented in harmful training examples \cite{ghosh2024aegis2}. This results in systematically higher false-positive rates for those groups. Since the system operates silently as an inline filter, affected users receive no feedback and have no recourse.

\textbf{Revised Design:} A demographic parity audit was added to the evaluation pipeline. If the false-positive rate for any identified dialect or style group exceeds that of the baseline group by more than 5 percentage points, a bias report is generated. The proposed safeguard requires that such a deployment be flagged for human review before going live. This does not eliminate the bias, which would require retraining, but makes it visible and creates an institutional obligation to address it.

